The game was originally available only on the R-18 version of DMM.com: DMM.R18, due to the H-scenes that the player can unlock based on an affection system (males have a conversation instead). body: [b]Operation Soda Steal[/b] was a 2008 plan made by GameFaqs user epitaphILIP who drew a picture where he planned to secretly "steal" several litres of [[Mountain Dew]] Baja Blast flavor soda, at a [[Taco Bell]] restaurant using a contraption hidden in his backpack and sleeve. The plan was well received with other users helping epitaphILIP how to build the device and succeed in his mission since at that time, Baja Blast was only available exclusively at Taco Bell due to a deal the restaurant made with Mountain Dew. Surprisingly, the plan not only went well but epitaphILIP even filmed video proof of the heist.

title: tetsuwan_birdy
body:
Also known as [b]Birdy the Mighty[/b], it is a manga series by [[Yuuki Masami]] initially made from 1985 to 1988. A reboot was produced that ran from 2002 until 2008. A four-episode OAV was also made in 1996, followed by a 25-episode anime from July 2008 to March 2009.

[[Birdy Cephon Altera]] is a Federation agent chasing interplanetary criminals to the planet Earth. While in pursuit of one such criminal, she accidentally kills a high school boy named [[Senkawa Tsutomu]]. However, there is a way to keep him alive. He ends up being merged into Birdy's body and must remain so until the repair of his body is complete. Tsutomu is stuck sharing a body with an attractive, strong, and impulsive space police agent while trying to keep his family and friends from finding out about Birdy. In the meantime, Birdy continues her investigation. Together, they take on a secretive group of evil aliens planning to perform experiments on the unsuspecting inhabitants of Earth.

title: cetme_model_58
body:
The CETME Model 58 is a Spanish [b][[battle rifle]][/b] which was designed in mid 1950s, produced by the state-owned [i]Centro de Estudios Técnicos de Materiales Especiales[/i] (CETME). Chambered for 7.62×51mm NATO and utilized standard 20-round [[magazine (weapon)|magazine]], its design consists of stamped metal receiver and roller-delayed blowback mechanism. title: diffraction_spikes
body:
Diffraction spikes manifest as multiple spikes radiating from a point of light, similar to a [[lens flare]] which manifests as overall haziness and artifacts in the image.

[[Sparkle]], [[glint]], and [b]diffraction spikes[/b] all refer to similar patterns of bright lines radiating from a point. They are not clearly differentiated, and usage tends to be context-sensitive. In general:
* [[Sparkle]] is considered the base case. Usually four lines at right angles radiating from a point. Associated with eyes, liquid or particulate matter (e.g. raindrops, snow, sand), or nothing (appearing mid-air). Can appear in large numbers.
* [[Glint]] is associated with solid objects, especially ones which are metallic and/or sharp. Usually appear singly or in small numbers.
* [b]Diffraction spikes[/b] is the technical term for the phenomenon in general, but is used less often. Can be used for more realistic-looking effects or conversely when appearing extremely large and exaggerated. More likely than sparkle and glint to be asymmetric or to have more than four radiating lines.

h4. See also

* [[bokeh]]
* [[light particles]]
* [[Tag group:Image Composition]]

h4. External Links

A hazmat suit (hazardous material suit) is a full body protective suit designed to protect the user from chemical, biological, nuclear or radiological hazards.

Most of them cover from head to toes and some are completely airtight.

They can be used with a [[gas mask]] to filter external air. Those with "positive pressure" (to guard against any fissure of the suit) have a balloon-like appearance.

May be seen at use during acts of [[terrorism]], plagues, the [[apocalypse]] or [[post-apocalypse]] scenarios. Their users might be doctors or members of public forces.

title: shining_shoot_(pose)
body:
Iconic pose from the opening of [i][[gundam_08th_ms_team|Mobile Suit Gundam: 08th MS Team]][/i]. It features an [[ground_gundam|RX-79G Gundam Ground Type]] firing a 180mm cannon, with a discarded shield in the foreground. The pose name derives from the shooting of the weapon, and the accompanying theme song [i]Arashi no Nakade de Kagayaite[/i] (嵐の中で輝いて, lit. 'Shining in the Storm').

Due to the angle and perspective, an optical illusion causes the barrel of the cannon to look to be balanced atop the upper rail of the shield. The comparative size of the shield to other appearances, and the brief motion of the barrel behind the rail disprove the effect on closer examination. Nevertheless, the perceived pose became so popular that was later replicated via effect parts in certain official merchandise.

title: genshiken
body:
[i][b]GENSHIKEN[/b][/i] (げんしけん) is a very popular manga created by [[Kio Shimoku]] about living in an [[otaku]] club. Is basically a "slice-of-life" comedy series focusing in otaku life and its consequences. 

The title is a shortening of the club's official name, [b]GEN[/b]dai [b]SHI[/b]kaku Bunka [b]KEN[/b]kyūkai (現代視覚文化研究会), which is translated as [i][b]The Society for the Study of Modern Visual Culture[/b][/i].

Serialized in Kodansha's [i]Afternoon[/i] from 2002-2006, the manga series continued for a second season as Genshiken II ([i]Genshiken Nidaime[/i] or [i]Genshiken Second Generation[/i]), which was released in December 2010 and ended in August 2016. 

The original manga was also adapted into two separate TV anime series by Genco in 2004 and 2007, as well as a 3 episode OVA in 2006. Additionally, Kio Shimoku announced in the manga that a new TV anime adaptation of the [i]Second Generation[/i] manga was in the works with the title [i]Genshiken Nidaime[/i] (げんしけん 二代目 - [i]Genshiken Second Generation[/i]), later airing in Japan from July 6 to September 29, 2013.

A [i]Genshiken Second Season OAD[/i] or Original Animation DVD was bundled with the limited edition of the 15th volume of the Genshiken manga. It was released in Dec 20, 2013 with the title [i]Genshiken Nidaime No Roku DVD[/i] (げんしけん オリジナルアニメDVD). The story is set between the events of Genshiken 2 and the Genshiken Nidaime series so none of the new characters from Nidaime appear in this anime.

A spin-off, [[Kujibiki Unbalance]], was produced by Ajia-do Animation Works in 2006, along with a manga, illustrated by [[Koume Keito]].

[[Spotted Flower]], a manga periodically illustrated and produced by Kio outside of Afternoon since 2009, is loosely based on Genshiken.

title: plasma-chan_(kancolle)
body:
A [[Kantai Collection]] meme character. A fanmade variation of [[Inazuma (kancolle)|]] that became meme enough to become a trend among Pixiv artists. She in originated in post #1917287 by [[Sukima (crie)|]].

She appears generally identical to Inazuma, but often a [[chibi]] figure (or deformed in a muscle-bound manner), and classically has a [[diamond mouth]] face with eyes that are [[solid_circle_eyes|large solid black circles]], upturned eyebrows, [[shaded_face|shading on her face]], and the oddly-shaped mouth twisted into a trolling smirk (see post #1680938). Frequently, she can be made to appear thuggish instead of smirking.  Plasma-chan is also a highly violent "dark-side" version of Inazuma, usually threatening people (or eggplants) with weapons or martial arts (see post #1726517). Alternately, simply behaving in a manner deliberately the opposite of the "pure and innocent" normal Inazuma (see post #1703511).

Plasma-chan was, in the Twitter images that originated her meme, violently opposed to an artist named [[Nasu (tenpurakkusu)|]] (Japanese for "[[eggplant]]") and featured the [[solid circle eyes]] and [[diamond mouth]] face as her salient traits in the series.  Some references to Plasma-chan just have her head and a "nasu" speech bubble. 

Inazuma's name means "lightning" in Japanese, so she becomes "plasma" as her dark side. 

Inazuma's catchphrase "[[nanodesu_(phrase)|]]" (なのです) may be [i]just slightly[/i] altered into "な゛の゛て゛す! (nano-DEATH!)" instead (alternately, "なの-DEATH!").

Dolan is an MS Paint web comic series featuring a variety of poorly drawn Disney cartoon characters. The main character Dolan, based on Donald Duck, is often portrayed as a psychotic killer and sex addict.

body:
A fan game-turned-official announced during MICA Team's 4th Anniversary Stream, May 15, 2020. A top-down side scrolling pixel-based adventure game set to star [[HK416 (girls' frontline)|]] as the main protagonist, set before the beginning of the core [[Girls' Frontline]] story. Was announced to be "shelved":https://www.reddit.com/r/girlsfrontline/comments/spz4e3/news_on_gfl_glitchland/ on February 11, 2021, a victim of increasing regulations on game registration in China (including the suspension of the approval of newly registered gaming IPs) preventing the game's release, with the original creator leaving Sunborn amicably and speaking favorably of his time there.

title: nes_gamepad
body:
The gamepad of the [[NES|Nintendo Entertainment System]], the version of the [[Famicom]] released outside of Japan.

While the NES console and its cartridges had an entirely different design compared to the Famicom, the controller was mostly the same in terms of layout.  The most noticeable difference is coloration. Where the [[Famicom gamepad]] has a red body, yellow front plate and all black buttons, the NES gamepad has a grey body, black front plate, and the A and B buttons are red. There are also three grey stripes over the Select and Start buttons.

title: animated_png
body:
An animated image in the APNG format, an unofficial, backwards-compatible extension to the PNG format created by the group behind Mozilla/Firefox. Comparable to [[animated gif]] files, but with support for 24-bit colour and 8-bit transparency.

Not fully supported by all browsers. Internet Explorer and EdgeHTML-based Microsoft Edge will only display a preview image, but the animation should display properly in Firefox, Chrome (v. 59 onwards), SeaMonkey, Safari, Opera (prior to v. 15) or Chromium-based Edge. Also note that the animation is not preserved when previewing or resizing the image, so make sure to click on "view original" if you wish to view more than the static preview image. In addition to these browsers, there is also support for the format in a few stand-alone image browsers. 

This tag is automatically added by the site to new uploads.

h4. See also

* [[Tag Group:Image Composition]]

h4. External links

* "Chrome Web Store: APNG for Chrome":https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/apng/ehkepjiconegkhpodgoaeamnpckdbblp (an extension for viewing APNGs in Chrome prior to v. 59)
* "XnView":http://www.xnview.com/en/ (a standalone image viewer with support for APNG)

title: alternate_language
body:
An image that has been hard-translated to another language (usually English) by the artist themselves, or by someone authorized by the artist (the company officially publishing a localization, a translator with the permission of the artist, etc).

In most cases the artist posts the translated version alongside the original version. In some cases the official translation may be poor quality, even though it was sanctioned by the artist.

This is different from [[hard-translated]], which is generally done by [[third-party_edit|third parties]].

title: hard-translated
body:
An image that has been [[third-party edit|edited]] by a third party to replace the original text (Japanese or otherwise) with a translation into English (or [[hard-translated (non-english)|another language]]).

This regularly occurs in [[comic|comics]] and [[doujinshi]], [[scan|scanlated]] or otherwise.

Uploading hard-translated images is discouraged, due to image quality issues, typographical issues, and the difficulty of confirming the correctness of the translations (see topic #2590 for discussion). The original image should be uploaded instead, and the translations applied via [[help:notes|notes]]. Non-original hard translations [[help:post relationships|should be made children]] of the original images whenever the latter can be found.

Posts that are hard-translated by the artist themselves should be tagged [[alternate language]] instead.

title: bydo
body:
バイド ([b]BYDO[/b]) is a recurring antagonist force in the [[R-Type]] series.

At first, nothing was known about the enemies known as the Bydo Empire other than their name. In [[R-TYPE III]], it was established that the Bydo were "the disastrous results of a gigantic composite biological weapon gone rogue, created by humankind in the 26th century".  (It is now the 22nd century.) However, because they are united under the entity known as the Bydo Core, the term "Bydo Empire" continues to be used out of convenience.

This life-form has a multitude of different forms, due to their ability to convert any type of matter, living or not, into their own. Naturally, the craft the player pilots is no exception.
Sentient beings that have been transformed into Bydo are often unaware of the changes in their own bodies. This tragic plot is one of the most popular elements of the game series.

title: manga_time_kirara

まんがタイムきらら (Manga Time Kirara) is a Japanese manga magazine published by Houbunsha, and is the first one focusing on moe [[4koma]] comic strips. Common themes include (but not limited to) slice-of-life and light-hearted [[yuri]]. The magazine, itself a spin-off of the Manga Time magazine, has spawned some number of sister magazines that are similarly named, including Manga Time Kirara Carat, MAX, Forward, Miracle, and Magica. 

Several of the series have been successful enough to receive anime adaptations. The openings of the anime adaptions are known for featuring the [[Kirara Jump]].

The magazine also has a cross-over game, [[Kirara Fantasia]], that brings together characters from different series in a fantasy setting.

title: namco
body:
A Japanese corporation best known as a former [[video game]] developer and publisher. Following a merger with [[Bandai]] in September 2005, the two companies' game production assets were spun off into [[Bandai Namco|Bandai Namco Games]] on March 31, 2006. Namco was re-established to continue domestic operation of video arcades and amusement parks. Its headquarters are located in Oota, Tokyo. The company's English name is officially often written as [b]NAMCO[/b] (in all capital letters).

Namco was a front-runner during the Golden age of [[arcade]] video games. [[Pac-Man]], its arguably most famous title, went on to become the best-selling arcade game in history and an international popular culture icon. They went on to create other hit franchises such as [[Splatterhouse]], [[Steel Gunner]], [[Tekken]], [[SoulCalibur]], [[Ridge Racer]], and [[Ace Combat]].

title: solar_eclipse
body:
An astronomical event where the moon passes between the sun and the earth, and the moon partially or completely covers the sun as viewed from a location on earth. This can only happen during a new moon, when the sun and moon are in conjunction as seen from earth.

A solar eclipse can be one of two major kinds: a partial eclipse, where the moon partially blocks out the sun; and a total eclipse, where the moon blocks out the sun completely and the sun's light creates a spectacular white ring around the moon.

Solar eclipses are frequently used in fiction to mark important, and often catastrophic, events in the plot.

title: hmas_stuart_(d00/i00)
body:
HMAS Stuart (Pennant Number: D00, later changed to I00) was a Scott class destroyer leader built between 1917-1919.
Served with the Royal Navy Mediterranean station until 1933 where she was transferred to the Royal Australian Navy where she served until being decommissioned and scrapped 1947 in Sydney.
She served as a Flotilla leader, with Captain 'Hec' Waller (killed later during the Battle of Sunda Strait, commanding HMAS Perth, 1942) commanding, for HMA Ships Vampire, Vendetta, Voyager and Waterhen.

Notable to have never taken a hit and never suffered a combat casualty her entire career despite being in multiple close range melees with enemy ships of larger class, most notably during the night following the Battle of Cape Matapan, going against Italian cruisers at point blank.
Also of note is that she spent more than half her combined service life in the Mediterranean in both the Royal Navy and Royal Australian Navy.

After returning from the Mediterranean, she was made a stores / fast transport vessel, being deemed 'too old' for a frontline destroyer, and spent the remainder of her life transporting supplies in and around the Papua New Guinea region until 1946.

title: adeleine
body:
Adeleine is a friend of [[Kirby]] and an artist who is best known for her ability to bring her creations to life.

Much like [[paint_roller_(kirby)|Paint Roller]] back from [i][[Kirby's Adventure]][/i], she can use paintings for combat, most notably in her boss fights. Unlike Paint Roller, she can only be attacked after she runs out from her easel (though she goes down in one hit).

While she's better known for her appearance in [i][[Kirby 64]][/i], she's implied to make her debut earlier in [i][[Kirby's Dream Land 3]][/i] under similar circumstances and a different name ("[[Ado (kirby)|]]", due to name space constraints). Due to differences in design between the two games, some fans like to distinguish the two appearances despite them possibly being the same character, calling the [i]Dream Land 3[/i] design "Ado" and the [i]64[/i] design  "Adeleine". In some cases, the two designs are drawn as twins.

She also appears in [i][[Kirby: Star Allies]][/i] as a Dream Friend with [[ribbon_(kirby)|Ribbon]] by her side. She is part of the second wave of post-launch Dream Friends alongside [[Daroach]] and [[Dark Meta Knight]].

Talim is a character from the [[Soulcalibur]] series. She made her debut in [[Soulcalibur II]].

The Last Priestess of the Winds, from the Village of the Wind Deity, she uses a pair of elbow blades called Syi Salika & Loka Luha for her agile fighting style.

She is the first fighting game character who originated from the Philippines, followed by [[Josie Rizal]] in Tekken 7, also made by Namco.

Her name means "sharp" (as an adjective) or "blade" in Tagalog, the officially spoken Filipino dialect.

title: scheherazade_(fate)
body:
Caster-class Servant in [[Fate/Grand Order]] who debuted in the Agartha singularity. Has [[long hair|long]] [[black hair]], [[dark-skinned female|dark skin]] and a [[curvy]] design featuring lots of [[skindentation]]. She is a character from the Middle Eastern story [i]One Thousand and One Nights[/i], where she dated a king who killed every woman he courted with so they wouldn't be unfaithful to him. Scheherazade avoided death by reading fascinating stories to the king every night, stopping the tale at dawn each time so she could keep his interest. After 1,001 nights together, the king spared her life and married her.

Usually grouped together with [[Nitocris (fate)|]] and [[Queen of Sheba (fate)|]] in both official and fan works due to their common traits as a middle eastern queen.

title: toyota_prius
body:
A hybrid [[car]] produced by [[Toyota]] starting in 1997. Early generations were often mocked for their bland designs and uninspiring performance, leading to later generations having gradually more aggressive designs in each iteration, and the latest generation featuring a distinctly futuristic design.
